<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-412-034  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 412 034.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MIS Week  April 9 1990 v11 n15 p20(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Machine translation: when computers speak in tongues, users savetime and money. (technology trends and products)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Feuche, Mike.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Machine translation (MT) software is rapidly becoming acost-effective productivity tool for a rapidly growing number ofusers.andP;  The increase in demand for translation software reflectsthe increased business that US companies do overseas.andP;  Thoseforeign customers want all the relevant documentation in theirnative language.andP;  Currently, MT software works well only withrepetitive text that lacks ambiguities, particularly technicalmaterial.andP;  The software packages can translate that kind of textfar faster than human translators, but the latter must stillpost-edit the translator's output to clean up the syntax andpolish the copy.andP;  MT also is far less costly than experttranslators, who enjoy salaries as high as $50,000 a year.andP;  MTpackages are available for 80286- and 80386-based PCs as well asminicomputers and IBM mainframes.andP;  Several MT products are brieflydescribed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Text CommunicationForeign LanguagesSoftware PackagesProductsSoftware PublishersLanguage Translation.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Major suppliers of machine translation software. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>